&lt;/div&gt;&lt;h3&gt;The Pumapungo museum&lt;/h3&gt;&lt;p&gt;We liked this museum mainly because of the outdoor part. There are archaeological excavations with a mock of an Inca garden and the characteristic terraces. You can find corn, quinoa, yucca, papas, kiwicha or chili peppers and find out more about the Inca diet. The Incas planted herbs and domesticated animals like parrots or lizards. What we didn&#39;t like at all was the exposition of parrots and even eagles and a condor in very small cages. Big shame on you, museum Pumapungo...&lt;br/&gt;The main building houses different expositions. We enjoyed the one dedicated to modern art on the ground floor. On the upper floor is an ethnological exposition which is very disorganized and poorly presented. The entrance is for free.&lt;/p&gt;
